## Modifying the assignment tree of an attribute
- Click on the name of the attribute whose assignment tree you wish to modify.

- Click on the node of the assignment tree you wish to modify.

- If you wish to change the node type, select a type from the selection bar.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

> Warning

If you change the type of a node, all the nodes which depend on it will be deleted. The node's properties may also change to reflect the new type.

## Changing the properties of a multiple selection node
A switch statement allows to compare a variable with a list of values. Each value is called a "case", and the variable being switched on is checked for each switch case. The default case can be used to perform a task when none of the cases is true.

- &nbsp;Click on the Multiple Selection node whose properties you wish to modify.

![](data:image/png;base64,) 

- From the allowed attributes panel, drag the attribute on which to perform the switch.

- &nbsp;Select a case and add the comparison value for the case and the value of the attribute if the case is true.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

 

> Warning

Due to an internal problem, if the attribute's Alignment option is set to " same as original ", when comparing a String attribute with a value for the case you must manually add padding on the right of the value in order to reach the total character length set for the attribute in the Length field, by adding the required number of trailing blanks, otherwise the case will not be matched.

For example, in order check if the value of a String attribute of 6 character is equal to "FE", you must add 4 extra spaces at the end of the comparison value for the case, i.

e. "FE  ", to match the attribute length.

This is also true if the String attribute contains a number. For example, if the value that you want to match is "151", it must include 3 extra spaces at the end, i.e. "151 ".

- Specify the default case, which will be used if none of the previous cases is true.

> Note

It is also possible to nest another switch within a switch condition, using the "default" case.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

To add a new case, click  ![](data:image/png;base64,)

To delete a case, select it and click  ![](data:image/png;base64,)

> Warning

Deletion of an exit from a Multiple Selection node does not require confirmation.

## Changing the properties of a single selection node
- Click on the Single Selection node whose properties you wish to modify.

- Select the type of connector for the selection from the **Logic Connector **menu.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

### Adding or deleting conditions
To add a selection condition, click **Condition**.

To delete a selection condition, select it and then click **Delete**.

> Warning

You may add up to 4 conditions. Deletion of a selection condition from a Single Selection node does not require confirmation.

## Changing a selection condition of a single selection node
Each condition consists of two operands and a comparison operator. Each of the two operands may be a constant value or an allowed attribute.

- Click on the Single Selection node whose properties you wish to modify.

- Click the condition you wish to switch.

- Select the type of each operand using the operand selection bar marked with the and icons.

- Type the value for each operand or drag one of the allowed attributes, depending on the type of selection you have made.

- Select the comparison operator from the operator selection menu.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Changing the properties of an expression node
- Click the Expression node whose properties you wish to modify.

- Select the desired operator from the **Operator **menu:

**Field type**

**Available operators**

**String**

- Concatenation

- Substring

- Replace

- Encode in xml

**Number**

- Addition

- Subtraction

- Multiplication

- Division

- Modulus

**Boolean**

- Odd Parity

- Even Parity

## Changing the properties of an expression for a String type attribute
### Changing the properties of a Concatenation expression
- Click the Expression node whose properties you wish to modify.

- From the **Operator **menu, select the value "**concatenate**" if not already selected.

- From the **Length** menu, select the desired concatenation mode:

 **fixed**

- **variable**

- (optional) In the **Separator **field, enter the text that you would like to use as a separator.

- If you wish to use constant elements in the concatenation, click **Constant **to add them, then click on the corresponding field to modify the text.

 To delete an element from the Concatenation, select it and then click **Delete**.

> Warning

No confirmation is required for deletion of an element from the Concatenation.

- If you wish to change the order of the elements in the Concatenation, drag them into the order required.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

### Changing the properties of a Substring expression
- Click the Expression node whose properties you wish to modify.

- From the **Operator **menu, select the value "**substring**" if not already selected.

- In the **From Character **field, enter the Substring starting position. "1" indicates the first character in the string.

- In the **Length **field, enter the length of the Substring.

- If you wish to use a constant element in the Substring, click **Constant **to add it, then click on the corresponding field to modify the text. &nbsp;

To delete an element from the Substring, click the name of the element then click **Delete operand**.

- If you wish to use a variable element in the Substring, drag it from the allowed attributes panel to the desired position.

> Warning

You may only specify one operand on which the Substring is performed. No confirmation is required for deletion of the operand.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

### Changing the properties of a Replace expression
- Click the Expression node whose properties you wish to modify.

- From the **Operator **menu, select the value "**replace**" if not already selected.

> Note

Replacement involves the application of various combinations of an operand to be found and an operand to be replaced for every positive result. A single replacement is created automatically.

- If you wish to add replacements, click **Replacement**. For each replacement, select the type of operand for the **Source **and **Replacement **c olumns using the operand selection bars.

- For each single substitution, type the value of the operand or drag one of the allowed attributes. &nbsp;

To delete a single substitution, select it and then **Delete **.

- If you wish to use a constant element in the Substitution, click **Constant **to add it, then click on the corresponding field to modify the text. &nbsp;

To delete an element from the Substitution, click the name of the element then click **Delete**.

- If you wish to use a variable element in the Substitution, drag it from the allowed attributes panel to the desired position.

> Warning

You may only specify one operand on which the Substitution is performed. No confirmation is required for deletion of the operand.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

### Changing the properties of a Encode in XML expression
- Click the Expression node whose properties you wish to modify.

- From the **Operator **menu, select the value "**encode from xml**" if not already selected.

- Insert the values that you want to encode in XML as constant or attribute reference. The value of the operand will be transformed so that it can be safely used as data in an XML attribute or text value.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Changing the properties of an expression for a Number type attribute
- Click the Expression node whose properties you wish to modify.

- From the **Operator **menu, select the type of expression:

**add**

- **subtract**

- **multiply **

- **divide**

- **module**

- If you wish to use a constant element in the Expression, click **Constant **to add it, then click on the corresponding field to modify the text. &nbsp;

 To delete an element from the Expression, select it and then click **Delete operand**.

- If you wish to change the order of the elements in the Expression, drag them to the desired position.

- If you wish to use variable elements in the Expression, drag them from the allowed attributes panel to the desired position.

> Warning

You may only use number attributes to generate an Expression that sets the value of a number attribute

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Changing the properties of an expression for a Boolean type attribute
- Click the Expression node whose properties you wish to modify.

- From the **Operator **menu, select the type of expression:

**even parity **

- **odd parity**

- If you wish to use a constant element in the Expression, click **Constant **to add it, then click on the corresponding field to modify the text. &nbsp;

To delete an element from the Expression, select it and then click **Delete**.

- If you wish to change the order of the elements in the Expression, drag them to the desired position.

- If you wish to use variable elements in the Expression, drag them from the allowed attributes panel into the desired position.

> Warning

You may only use Boolean attributes to generate an Expression that sets the value of a Boolean attribute.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Changing the properties of a Constant node
- Click the Constant node whose properties you wish to modify.

- &nbsp;Enter a value in the box marked with the icon.

![](data:image/png;base64,) 

> Warning

If the attribute to which the constant has been assigned is of Number type, you will have to enter a numerical value:

![](data:image/png;base64,) if it is of Boolean type, you cannot enter a value of your choice but only choose between true and false:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Changing the properties of a Reference node
- Click the Reference node whose properties you wish to modify.

- Drag one of the allowed attributes into the box marked with the icon.

> Warning

If the attribute to which you are assigning the constant is of Number type, you will have to select a Number attribute; if it is of Boolean type, you will have to select a Boolean attribute.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Changing the properties of an Attachment node
The logic of the attachment attribute is configured in Campaign Management and automatically injected into Output Management. It is only possible to define the attribute and use its value for the usual OM logic. The Campaign Management module will read the OM-defined attachments and allow their configuration.
